article.description:
Kamila Vodichkova scored a season-high 20 points
and rookie Sue Bird added 16 as the Seattle Storm snapped a
three-game losing streak with a 63-51 victory over the Indiana
Fever on Friday night.
article.headline: Storm holds on to defeat Fever
article.linkText: Vodichkova, Bird help Storm end three-game losing skid
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle Storm got back to team defense and
back to winning.

	   Kamila Vodichkova scored 17 of her season-high 20 points in the
first half as Seattle defeated the Indiana Fever 63-51 Friday
night.

	   "I'm really pleased with Kamila,'' head coach Lin Dunn said.
"She set the tone for us early.''

	   Rookie Sue Bird tossed in 16 points and four assists as Seattle
(5-6) ended a three-game losing streak.

	   Seattle opened the game on a 18-3 run as Vodichkova scored 13 of
the Storm's points. Her 17 points in the first half tied a team
record shared by four others.

	   "My plan coming in was just to win,'' Vodichkova said of her
early success. "I wanted to focus on taking more shots, but our
team defense is what really supported me.''

	   Indiana (5-6) turned the ball over 14 times in the first half
which led to 24 Storm points. The Fever finished with 17 turnovers
for the game.

	   "Seattle played great defensively and they held their ground,''
Indiana head coach Nell Fortner said of her team's loss.

	   Olympia Scott-Richard had 12 points and reserve Kelly Schumacher
scored 11.

	   Tamika Catchings had 11 points for the Fever. Catchings came
into the game third in league scoring averaging more than 19
points.

	   Newly acquired Amanda Lassiter chipped in eight points for the
Storm, but was more of a factor defensively. Lassiter played in
only her second game for Seattle since coming over in a trade from
the Houston Comets for Sonja Henning.

	   "Lassiter and company did a great job I thought on Catchings,''
Dunn said. "She's just now getting use to the team and will only
get better.''

	   Catchings wasn't happy.

	   "We didn't play very well,'' she said. "Their defense took us
out of our game.''

	   Seattle led by as many as 25 points midway through the second
half, when Vodichkova drained a 3-pointer from the top of the key.

	   An Indiana run late got the Fever within 59-44, with 3:30
remaining, but late baskets by Bird and Jackson secured the win.

	   "All of our games have had good starts,'' Bird said. "Tonight
we just maintained that energy and fought off their run.''

	   The Storm lead at the half, 41-22, after back-to-back 3s by Bird
and Lassiter. Indiana's only lead was 2-0.
